    When drawCycle reaches totalDraws, the if block is skipped. instance.state.transform retains its last computed value — the sprite freezes in place. This matches Scala: once spriteDrawCount >= spriteTotalDraws, animator.update()  
  is never called, so the sprite holds its last geometric state.
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       
  Why drawCycle and not elapsed time: totalDraws in the XML is in virtual draw-cycle units (integer), and drawCycle is incremented exactly once per virtual frame boundary. Time-based comparison would drift at non-target frame      
  rates. This gives the precise "exactly 10 draw cycles" behavior the user described.
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       
  Global animating master switch: Added a guard in LoomEngine.advance — when globalConfig.animating == false, scene.advance is not called at all. Sprites stay frozen at their initial positions. Previously this flag only controlled 
  the EngineController's initial playback state, not the engine itself. Now it's a proper engine-level gate.
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       
  Draw cycles vs temporal duration: Both are already expressible. totalDraws is the cycle count (integer, exact). For time-based limits you'd set totalDraws = desiredSeconds * targetFPS. The cycle-count approach is what the XML    
  stores and what Test_060 uses (10 cycles).


